) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def countTriplets(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Initialize the count of triplets\n        count = 0\n        n = len(arr)\n        \n        # Iterate over all possible starting points i\n        for i in range(n):\n            xor_sum = 0\n            # Iterate over all possible ending points k\n            for k in range(i, n):\n                # Calculate the xor from i to k\n                xor_sum ^= arr[k]\n                # If xor_sum is 0, it means we found valid (i, j, k) triplets\n                # where a == b, and there are (k - i) such triplets\n                if xor_sum == 0:\n                    count += (k - i)\n        \n        return count\n```\n\nThis solution iterates over all possible pairs of starting and ending indices (i, k) and calculates the cumulative XOR from index i to k. If the cumulative XOR is zero, it indicates that there exists at least one valid j such that the XOR of the subarrays a and b are equal. The number of such valid j's for a given (i, k) pair is (k - i), which is added to the count. This approach ensures that all possible triplets (i, j, k) are considered, and it meets the problem's constraints.", "estimated_date": 1589068800000}